# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phishing-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] Most popular web browsers comes with built-in anti-phishing and anti-malware protection services, but almost none of the alternate web browsers have such protections.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] Password managers can also be used to help defend against phishing, as can some mutual authentication techniques.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] Of the solutions tested, Netcraft Toolbar, EarthLink ScamBlocker and SpoofGuard were able to correctly identify over 75% of the sites tested, with Netcraft Toolbar receiving the highest score without incorrectly identifying legitimate sites as phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] The testing was performed using phishing data obtained from Anti-Phishing Working Group, PhishTank, and an unnamed email filtering vendor.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] Another study, conducted by SmartWare for Mozilla and released November 14, 2006, concluded that the anti-phishing filter in Firefox was more effective than Internet Explorer by over 10%.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] The results of this study have been questioned by critics, noting that the testing data was sourced from PhishTank, which itself is an anti-phishing provider.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] The study only compared Internet Explorer and Firefox, leaving out (among others) Netcraft Toolbar and the Opera browser, both of which use data from PhishTank in their anti-phishing solutions.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] This has led to speculations that, with the limited testing data, both Opera and Netcraft Toolbar would have got a perfect score had they been part of the study.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] While these two reports were released only one day apart, Asa Dotzler, Director of Community Development at Mozilla, has responded to the criticism of the Mozilla-commissioned report by saying, "so you're agreeing that the most recent legitimate data puts Firefox ahead.
[src:phishing-defense/anti-phishing-software] Since these studies were conducted, both Microsoft and Opera Software have started licensing Netcraft's anti-phishing data, bringing the effectiveness of their browser's built-in anti-phishing on par with Netcraft Toolbar.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Once the DMARC DNS entry is published, any receiving email server can authenticate the incoming email based on the instructions published by the domain owner within the DNS entry.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] If the email passes the authentication, it will be delivered and can be trusted.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] If the email fails the check, depending on the instructions held within the DMARC record the email could be delivered, quarantined or rejected.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC extends two existing email authentication mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] It allows the administrative owner of a domain to publish a policy in their DNS records to specify how to check the `From:` field presented to end users and how the receiver should deal with failures, and it provides a reporting mechanism for actions performed under those policies.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC is defined in the Internet Engineering Task Force's published document RFC 9989, dated May 2026, as "Standards Track".
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A DMARC policy allows a sender's domain to indicate that their email messages are protected by SPF and/or DKIM, and tells a receiver what to do if neither of those authentication methods passes – such as to reject the message or quarantine it.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The policy can also specify how an email receiver can report back to the sender's domain about messages that pass and/or fail.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] These policies are published in the public Domain Name System (DNS) as text TXT records.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC does not directly address whether or not an email is spam or otherwise fraudulent.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Instead, DMARC can require that a message not only pass DKIM or SPF validation, but that it also pass § Alignment.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Under DMARC a message can fail even if it passes SPF or DKIM but fails alignment.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Setting up DMARC may improve the deliverability of messages from legitimate senders.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC operates by checking that the domain in the message's `From:` field (also called "RFC5322.From") is "aligned" with other authenticated domain names.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] If either SPF (specified using the `aspf` field) or DKIM (specified using the `adkim` field) alignment checks pass, then the DMARC alignment test passes.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Alignment may be specified as strict or relaxed.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] For strict alignment, the domain names must be identical.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] For relaxed alignment, the top-level "Organizational Domain" must match.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The Organizational Domain used to be found by checking a list of public DNS suffixes.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The upcoming spec instead specifies a Tree Walk through the parent domains.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] So, for example, "a.b.c.d.example.com.au" and "example.com.au" have the same Organizational Domain, because _dmarc.example.com.au is the only defined DMARC record among all the subdomains involved, including _dmarc.au.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] As this allows domain owners to define domain roles, it is deemed to be more accurate than the Public Suffix List.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Like SPF and DKIM, DMARC uses the concept of a domain owner, the entity or entities authorized to make changes to a given DNS domain.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] SPF checks that the IP address of the sending server is authorized by the owner of the domain that appears in the SMTP `MAIL FROM` command.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] (The email address in MAIL FROM is also called the bounce address, envelope-from or RFC5321.MailFrom.) In addition to requiring that the SPF check passes, DMARC checks that RFC5321.MailFrom aligns with 5322.From.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DKIM allows parts of an email message to be cryptographically signed, and the signature must cover the From field.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Within the DKIM-Signature mail header, the `d=` (domain) and `s=` (selector) tags specify where in DNS to retrieve the public key for the signature.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A valid signature proves that the signer is a domain owner, and that the From field hasn't been modified since the signature was applied.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] There may be several DKIM signatures on an email message; DMARC requires one valid signature where the domain in the `d=` tag aligns with the sender's domain stated in the `From:` header field.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC records are published in DNS with a subdomain label `_dmarc`, for example `_dmarc.example.com`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Compare this to SPF at `example.com`, and DKIM at `selector._domainkey.example.com`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The content of the TXT resource record consists of `name=value` tags, separated by semicolons, similar to SPF and DKIM.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In this example, the entity controlling the example.com DNS domain intends to monitor SPF and/or DKIM failure rates and doesn't expect email to be sent from subdomains of example.com.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Note that a subdomain can publish its own DMARC record; receivers must check it out before falling back to the organizational domain record.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The protocol provides for various ratchets, or transitional states, to allow mail admins to gradually transition from not implementing DMARC at all, all the way through to an unyielding setup.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The concept of stepwise adoption assumes that the goal of DMARC is the strongest setting, which is not the case for all domains.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Regardless of intent, these mechanisms allow for greater flexibility.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The policy published can be mitigated by applying it to only a percentage of the messages that fail DMARC check.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Receivers are asked to select the given percentage of messages by a simple Bernoulli sampling algorithm.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The rest of the messages should undergo the lower policy; that is, none if `p=quarantine`, quarantine if `p=reject`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] If not specified, pct defaults to 100% of messages.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The case `p=quarantine; pct=0;` is being used to force mailing list managers to rewrite the From: field, as some don't do so when `p=none`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Finally, the subdomain policy, `sp=` and the newly added no-domain policy, `np=` allow tweaking the policy for specific subdomains.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC is capable of producing two separate types of reports.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Aggregate reports are sent to the address specified following the `rua`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Forensic reports are emailed to the address following the `ruf` tag.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] These mail addresses must be specified in URI mailto format (e.g. mailto:worker@example.net ).
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Multiple reporting addresses are valid and must each be in full URI format, separated by a comma.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Target email addresses can belong to external domains.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In that case, the target domain has to set up a DMARC record to say it agrees to receive them, otherwise it would be possible to exploit reporting for spam amplification.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] For example, say `receiver.example` receives a mail message `From: someone@sender.example` and wishes to report it.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Aggregate Reports are sent as XML files, typically once per day.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The subject mentions the "Report Domain", which indicates the DNS domain name about which the report was generated, and the "Submitter", which is the entity issuing the report.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The XML content consists of a header, containing the policy on which the report is based and report metadata, followed by a number of records.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Records can be put in a database as a relation and viewed in a tabular form.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The XML schema is defined in Appendix C of specifications and a raw record is exemplified in dmarc.org.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Here we stick with a relational example, which better conveys the nature of the data.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC records can also be directly transformed in HTML by applying an XSL stylesheet.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Rows are grouped by source IP and authentication results, passing just the count of each group.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The leftmost result columns, labelled **SPF** and **DKIM** show DMARC-wise results, either pass or fail, taking alignment into account.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The rightmost ones, with similar labels, show the name of the domain which claims to participate in the sending of the message and (in parentheses) the authentication status of that claim according to the original protocol, SPF or DKIM, regardless of Identifier Alignment.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] On the right side, SPF can appear at most twice, once for the `Return-Path:` test and once for the `HELO` test; DKIM can appear once for each signature present in the message.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In the example, the first row represents the main mail flow from example.org, and the second row is a DKIM glitch, such as signature breakage due to a minor alteration in transit.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The third and fourth rows show typical failures modes of a forwarder and a mailing list, respectively.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] DMARC authentication failed for the last row only; it could have affected the message disposition if example.org had specified a strict policy.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The **disposition** reflects the policy published actually applied to the messages, *none*, *quarantine*, or *reject*.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Along with it, not shown in the table, DMARC provides for a policy override.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] if none of the above applies, a comment field allows to say more.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Failure Reports, also known as Forensic Reports, are generated in real time and consist of possibly redacted copies of individual messages that failed SPF, DKIM or both based upon what value is specified in the `fo` tag.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Their format, an extension of Abuse Reporting Format, resembles that of regular bounces in that they contain either a "message/rfc822" or a "text/rfc822-headers".
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] There are several different types of email forwarding, some of which may break SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] This is one of the reasons why email forwarding can affect DMARC authentication results.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Mailing lists are a frequent cause of legitimate breakage of the original author's domain DKIM signature, for example by adding a prefix to the subject header.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A number of workarounds are possible, and mailing list software packages are working on solutions.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] This workaround keeps the standard mailing list workflow, and is adopted by several large mailing list operators, but precludes the list adding footers and subject prefixes.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] This requires careful configuration of mailing software to make sure signed headers are not reordered or modified.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A misconfigured email server may put List-id in its DKIM of messages sent to a mailing list, and then the list operator is forced to reject it or do From: rewriting.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] One of the most popular and least intrusive workarounds consists of rewriting the `From:` header field.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The original author's address can then be added to the `Reply-To:` field.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Rewriting can range from just appending `.INVALID` to the domain name, to allocating a temporary user ID where a modified version of the user's address is used, or an opaque ID is used, which keeps the user's "real" email address private from the list.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In addition, the display name can be changed so as to show both the author and the list (or list operator).
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The last line, `Reply-To:`, has to be designed in order to accommodate reply-to-author functionality, in which case reply-to-list functionality is covered by the preceding change in the `From:` header field.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] That way, the original meaning of those fields is reversed.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Altering the author is not fair in general, and can break the expected relationship between meaning and appearance of that datum.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] There are communities which use mailing lists to coordinate their work, and deploy tools which use the `From:` field to attribute authorship to attachments.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Wrapping the message works nicely, for those who use an email client which understands wrapped messages.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Not doing any change is perhaps the most obvious solution, except that they seem to be legally required in some countries, and that routinely losing SPF authentication may render overall authentication more fragile.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The `Sender:` header is available to indicate that an email was sent on behalf of another party, but DMARC only checks policy for the From domain and ignores the Sender domain.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Both ADSP and DMARC reject using the Sender field on the non-technical basis that many user agents do not display this to the recipient.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A draft DMARC specification has been maintained since 30 January 2012.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In October 2013, GNU Mailman 2.1.16 was released with options to handle posters from a domain with the DMARC policy of `p=reject`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] The change tried to anticipate the interoperability issues expected in case restrictive policies were applied to domains with human users (as opposed to purely transactional mail domains).
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In April 2014, Yahoo changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`, thereby causing misbehavior in several mailing lists.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] A few days later, AOL also changed its DMARC policy to `p=reject`.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Those moves resulted in a significant amount of disruption, and those mailbox providers have been accused of forcing the costs of their own security failures onto third parties.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] As of 2020, the FAQ in the official DMARC wiki contains several suggestions for mailing lists to handle messages from a domain with a strict DMARC policy, of which the most widely implemented is the mailing list changing the “From” header to an address in its own domain.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] An IETF working group was formed in August 2014 in order to address DMARC issues, starting from interoperability concerns and possibly continuing with a revised standard specification and documentation.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Meanwhile, the existing DMARC specification had reached an editorial state agreed upon and implemented by many.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] It was published in March 2015 on the Independent Submission stream in the "Informational" (non-standard) category as RFC 7489.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] In March 2017, the Federal Trade Commission published a study on DMARC usage by businesses.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Out of 569 businesses, the study found about a third implemented any DMARC configuration, fewer than 10% used DMARC to instruct servers to reject unauthenticated messages, and a majority had implemented SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] An updated RFC 9989 was published in May 2026.
[src:phishing-defense/dmarc] Popular services that perform DMARC analysis and/or record validation include Red Sift, Valimail, dmarcian, DMARC Advisor and EasyDmarc and Cloudflare.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The receiver can check that an email that claimed to have come from a specific domain was indeed authorized by the owner of that domain.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It achieves this by affixing a digital signature, linked to a domain name, to each outgoing email message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The recipient system can verify this by looking up the sender's public key published in the DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A valid signature also guarantees that some parts of the email (possibly including attachments) have not been modified since the signature was affixed.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Usually, DKIM signatures are not visible to end-users, and are affixed or verified by the infrastructure rather than the message's authors and recipients.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is defined in RFC 6376, dated September 2011, with updates in RFC 8301, RFC 8463, RFC 8553, and RFC 8616.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The need for email validated identification arises because forged addresses and content are otherwise easily created—and widely used in spam, phishing and other email-based fraud.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, a fraudster may send a message claiming to be from *sender@example.com*, with the goal of convincing the recipient to accept and to read the email—and it is difficult for recipients to establish whether to trust this message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] System administrators also have to deal with complaints about malicious emails that appear to have originated from their systems, but did not.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM provides the ability to sign a message, and allows the signer (*author* organization) to communicate which email it considers legitimate.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It does not directly prevent or disclose abusive behavior.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM also provides a process for verifying a signed message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Verifying modules typically act on behalf of the *receiver* organization, possibly at each hop.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] All of this is independent of Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) routing aspects, in that it operates on the RFC 5322 message—the transported mail's header and body—not the SMTP "envelope" defined in RFC 5321.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Hence, DKIM signatures survive basic relaying across multiple message transfer agents.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The signing organization can be a direct handler of the message, such as the author, mail submission agent, site, or further intermediary along the transit path, or an indirect handler such as an independent service that is providing assistance to a direct handler.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Signing modules insert one or more `DKIM-Signature:` header fields, possibly on behalf of the *author* organization or the originating service provider.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The specification allows signers to choose which header fields they sign, but the `From:` field must always be signed.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The most relevant ones are **b** for the actual digital signature of the contents (headers and body) of the mail message, **bh** for the body hash (optionally limited to the first **l** octets of the body), **d** for the signing domain, and **s** for the selector.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] An Agent or User Identifier (AUID) can optionally be included.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The format is an email address with an optional local-part.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The domain must be equal to, or a subdomain of, the signing domain.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The semantics of the AUID are intentionally left undefined, and may be used by the signing domain to establish a more fine-grained sphere of responsibility.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Both header and body contribute to the signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] First, the message body is hashed, always from the beginning, possibly truncated to a given length **l** (which may be zero).
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Second, selected header fields are hashed, in the order given by **h**.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Repeated field names are matched from the bottom of the header upward, which is the order in which `Received:` fields are inserted in the header.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A non-existing field matches the empty string, so that adding a field with that name will break the signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The `DKIM-Signature:` field of the signature being created, with **bh** equal to the computed body hash and **b** equal to the empty string, is implicitly added to the second hash, albeit its name must not appear in **h** — if it does, it refers to another, preexisting signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For both hashes, text is canonicalized according to the relevant **c** algorithms.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The result, after encryption with the signer's private key and encoding using Base64, is **b**.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition to the list of header fields listed in **h**, a list of header fields (including both field name and value) present at the time of signing may be provided in **z**.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This list need not match the list of headers in **h**.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Algorithms, fields, and body length are meant to be chosen so as to assure unambiguous message identification while still allowing signatures to survive the unavoidable changes which are going to occur in transit.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] No end-to-end data integrity is implied.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A receiving SMTP server wanting to verify uses the domain name and the selector to perform a DNS lookup.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, given the example signature above: the **d** tag gives the *author* domain to be verified against, *example.net* ; the **s** tag the selector, *brisbane*.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The string *_domainkey* is a fixed part of the specification.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Note that the selector and the domain name can be UTF-8 in internationalized email.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In that case the label must be encoded according to IDNA before lookup.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The data returned from the query of this record is also a list of tag-value pairs.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A CNAME record can also be used to point at a different TXT record, for example when one organization sends email on behalf of another.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The receiver can use the public key (value of the **p** tag) to then validate the signature on the hash value in the header field, and check it against the hash value for the mail message (headers and body) that was received.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] If the two values match, this cryptographically proves that the mail was signed by the indicated domain and has not been tampered with in transit.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Signature verification failure does not force rejection of the message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, the precise reasons why the authenticity of the message could not be proven should be made available to downstream and upstream processes.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Methods for doing so may include sending back an FBL message, or adding an `Authentication-Results:` header field to the message as described in RFC 7001.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DomainKeys was covered by U.S. patent 6,986,049, now expired.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Yahoo! licensed its patent claims under a dual license scheme: the *DomainKeys Patent License Agreement v1.2*, or *GNU General Public License v2.0 (and no other version)*.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In essence, both DKIM and SPF provide different measures of email authenticity.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The primary advantage of this system for e-mail recipients is in allowing the signing domain to reliably identify a stream of legitimate email, thereby allowing domain-based blacklists and whitelists to be more effective.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This is also likely to make certain kinds of phishing attacks easier to detect.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM is a method of labeling a message, and it does not itself filter or identify spam.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, widespread use of DKIM can prevent spammers from forging the source address of their messages, a technique they commonly employ today.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] If spammers are forced to show a correct source domain, other filtering techniques can work more effectively.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In particular, the source domain can feed into a reputation system to better identify spam.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Conversely, DKIM can make it easier to identify mail that is known not to be spam and need not be filtered.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] If a receiving system has a whitelist of known good sending domains, either locally maintained or from third party certifiers, it can skip the filtering on signed mail from those domains, and perhaps filter the remaining mail more aggressively.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM can be useful as an anti-phishing technology.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Mailers in heavily phished domains can sign their mail to show that it is genuine.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Recipients can take the absence of a valid signature on mail from those domains to be an indication that the mail is probably forged.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The best way to determine the set of domains that merit this degree of scrutiny remains an open question.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM used to have an optional feature called ADSP that lets authors that sign all their mail self-identify, but it was demoted to historic status in November 2013.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, DMARC can be used for the same purpose and allows domains to self-publish which techniques (including SPF and DKIM) they employ, which makes it easier for the receiver to make an informed decision whether a certain mail is spam or not.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For example, using DMARC, eBay and PayPal both publish policies that all of their mail is authenticated, and requesting that any receiving system, such as Gmail, should reject any that is not.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Because it is implemented using DNS records and an added RFC 5322 header field, DKIM is compatible with the existing e-mail infrastructure.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In particular, it is transparent to existing e-mail systems that lack DKIM support.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This design approach also is compatible with other, related services, such as the S/MIME and OpenPGP content-protection standards.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM is compatible with the DNSSEC standard and with SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM requires cryptographic checksums to be generated for each message sent through a mail server, which results in computational overhead not otherwise required for e-mail delivery.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This additional computational overhead is a hallmark of digital postmarks, making sending bulk spam more (computationally) expensive.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This facet of DKIM may look similar to hashcash, except that the receiver side verification is a negligible amount of work, while a typical hashcash algorithm would require far more work.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM's non-repudiation feature prevents senders (such as spammers) from credibly denying having sent an email.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It has proven useful to news media sources such as WikiLeaks, which has been able to leverage DKIM body signatures to prove that leaked emails were genuine and not tampered with.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In practice, it is hard to verify many old emails due to key rotation and difficulty in finding the original keys before rotation, as they are not published anywhere.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] One way to verify old emails is to use archives that collect signatures and selectors from existing emails, and can recover expired public keys from pairs of signatures done by the same key.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Green considers non-repudiation a non-wanted feature of DKIM, forced by behaviors such as those just described.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Indeed, DKIM protocol provides for expiration.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] There is an optional **x** tag on each signature, which establishes a formal expiration time; however, verifiers can ignore it.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition, domain owners can revoke a public key by removing its cryptographic data from the record, thereby preventing signature verification unless someone saved the public key data beforehand.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM key rotation is often recommended just to minimize the impact of compromised keys.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, in order to definitely disable non-repudiation, expired secret keys can be published, thereby allowing everyone to produce fake signatures, thus voiding the significance of original ones.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] By default, publishing a redacted email is not verifiable because the DKIM body hashes cannot be constructed.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, you can still verify such emails if the owner creates a zero-knowledge proof of the DKIM signature on a masked subset of headers or body text, while constraining the disclosed portions match the signed message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Implementations often use regex or masking to hide or show selected content.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This proof can be provided instead of a DKIM signature to third parties in order for anyone to verify the validity of the email.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] These proofs can even be generated locally on a user's device, so that the redacted information is never sent to third parties.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It can be used to create secure anonymous message boards with private identities but verified affiliations, like a fully private Blind.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It can also be used when authenticating a sender's claim is needed, but the recipient wants to remain anonymous.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The RFC itself identifies a number of potential attack vectors.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM signatures do not encompass the message envelope, which holds the return-path and message recipients.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Since DKIM does not attempt to protect against mis-addressing, this does not affect its utility.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A number of concerns were raised and refuted in 2013 at the time of the standardization.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A concern for any cryptographic solution would be message replay abuse, which bypasses techniques that currently limit the level of abuse from larger domains.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Replay can be inferred by using per-message public keys, tracking the DNS queries for those keys and filtering out the high number of queries due to e-mail being sent to large mailing lists or malicious queries by bad actors.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For a comparison of different methods also addressing this problem see e-mail authentication.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] As mentioned above, authentication is not the same as abuse prevention.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A malicious email user of a reputable domain can compose a bad message and have it DKIM-signed and sent from that domain to any mailbox from where they can retrieve it as a file, so as to obtain a signed copy of the message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Use of the **l** tag in signatures makes doctoring such messages even easier.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The signed copy can then be forwarded to a million recipients, for example through a botnet, without control.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The email provider who signed the message can block the offending user, but cannot stop the diffusion of already-signed messages.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The validity of signatures in such messages can be limited by always including an expiration time tag in signatures, or by revoking a public key periodically or upon a notification of an incident.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Effectiveness of the scenario can hardly be limited by filtering outgoing mail, as that implies the ability to detect if a message might potentially be useful to spammers.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM currently features two canonicalization algorithms, simple and relaxed, neither of which is MIME-aware.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Mail servers can legitimately convert to a different character set, and often document this with `X-MIME-Autoconverted:` header fields.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In addition, servers in certain circumstances have to rewrite the MIME structure, thereby altering the *preamble*, the *epilogue*, and entity boundaries, any of which breaks DKIM signatures.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Only plain text messages written in us-ascii, provided that MIME header fields are not signed, enjoy the robustness that end-to-end integrity requires.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The OpenDKIM Project organized a data collection involving 21 mail servers and millions of messages.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] 92.3% of observed signatures were successfully verified, a success rate that drops slightly (90.5%) when only mailing list traffic is considered.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The problems might be exacerbated when filtering or relaying software makes changes to a message.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Without specific precaution implemented by the sender, the footer addition operated by most mailing lists and many central antivirus solutions will break the DKIM signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A possible mitigation is to sign only designated number of bytes of the message body.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is indicated by **l** tag in **DKIM-Signature** header.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Anything added beyond the specified length of the message body is not taken into account while calculating DKIM signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Another workaround is to whitelist known forwarders; e.g., by SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] For yet another workaround, it was proposed that forwarders verify the signature, modify the email, and then re-sign the message with a Sender: header.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, this solution has its risk with forwarded third party signed messages received at SMTP receivers supporting the RFC 5617 ADSP protocol.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Thus, in practice, the receiving server still has to whitelist known *message streams*.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The Authenticated Received Chain (ARC) is an email authentication system designed to allow an intermediate mail server like a mailing list or forwarding service to sign an email's original authentication results.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This allows a receiving service to validate an email when the email's SPF and DKIM records are rendered invalid by an intermediate server's processing.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] ARC is defined in RFC 8617, published in July 2019, as "Experimental".
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In October 2012, *Wired* reported that mathematician Zach Harris detected and demonstrated an email source spoofing vulnerability with short DKIM keys for the `google.com` corporate domain, as well as several other high-profile domains.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] He stated that authentication with 384-bit keys can be factored in as little as 24 hours "on my laptop," and 512-bit keys, in about 72 hours with cloud computing resources.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Harris found that many organizations sign email with such short keys; he factored them all and notified the organizations of the vulnerability.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] He states that 768-bit keys could be factored with access to very large amounts of computing power, so he suggests that DKIM signing should use key lengths greater than 1,024.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] DKIM resulted in 2004 from merging two similar efforts, "enhanced DomainKeys" from Yahoo and "Identified Internet Mail" from Cisco.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] This merged specification has been the basis for a series of IETF standards-track specifications and support documents which eventually resulted in STD 76, currently RFC 6376.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] "Identified Internet Mail" was proposed by Cisco as a signature-based mail authentication standard, while DomainKeys was designed by Yahoo to verify the DNS domain of an e-mail sender and the message integrity.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Aspects of DomainKeys, along with parts of Identified Internet Mail, were combined to create DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Trendsetting providers implementing DKIM include Yahoo, Gmail, AOL and FastMail.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Any mail from these organizations should carry a DKIM signature.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Discussions about DKIM signatures passing through indirect mail flows, formally in the DMARC working group, took place right after the first adoptions of the new protocol wreaked havoc on regular mailing list use.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] However, none of the proposed DKIM changes passed.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Instead, mailing list software was changed.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In 2017, another working group was launched, DKIM Crypto Update (dcrup), with the specific restriction to review signing techniques.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It adds an elliptic curve algorithm to the existing RSA.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The added key type, `k=ed25519` is adequately strong while featuring short public keys, more easily publishable in DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] The original *DomainKeys* was designed by Mark Delany of Yahoo! and enhanced through comments from many others since 2004.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] It is specified in Historic RFC 4870, superseded by Standards Track RFC 4871, DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM) Signatures; both published in May 2007.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] A number of clarifications and conceptualizations were collected thereafter and specified in RFC 5672, August 2009, in the form of corrections to the existing specification.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In September 2011, RFC 6376 merged and updated the latter two documents, while preserving the substance of the DKIM protocol.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Public key compatibility with the earlier DomainKeys is also possible.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Source code development of one common library is led by *The OpenDKIM Project*, following the most recent protocol additions, and licensing under the New BSD License.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Email providers are increasingly requiring senders to implement email authentication in order to successfully deliver mail to their users' mailboxes.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] In February 2024, Google started requiring bulk senders to authenticate their emails with DKIM to successfully deliver emails to Google-hosted mailboxes.
[src:phishing-defense/domainkeys-identified-mail] Similarly in February 2024, Yahoo started requiring bulk senders to implement SPF and DKIM to successfully deliver emails to Yahoo users.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The original base of Internet email, Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), has no such feature, so forged sender addresses in emails (a practice known as email spoofing) have been widely used in phishing, email spam, and various types of frauds.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] To combat this, many competing email authentication proposals have been developed.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] By 2018 three had been widely adopted – SPF, DKIM and DMARC.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The results of such validation can be used in automated email filtering, or can assist recipients when selecting an appropriate action.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] This article does not cover user authentication of email submission and retrieval.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] In the early 1980s, when Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) was designed, it provided for no real verification of sending user or system.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] This was not a problem while email systems were run by trusted corporations and universities, but since the commercialization of the Internet in the early 1990s, spam, phishing, and other crimes have been found to increasingly involve email.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Email authentication is a necessary first step towards identifying the origin of messages, and thereby making policies and laws more enforceable.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Hinging on domain ownership is a stance that emerged in the early 2000.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] It implies a coarse-grained authentication, given that domains appear on the right part of email addresses, after the at sign.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Fine-grained authentication, at a user level, can be achieved by other means, such as Pretty Good Privacy and S/MIME.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] At present, each individual must ultimately manage their own digital identity.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] An outstanding rationale for email authentication is the ability to automate email filtering at receiving servers.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] That way, spoofed messages can be rejected before they arrive to a user's inbox.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] While protocols strive to devise ways to reliably block distrusted mail, security indicators can tag unauthenticated messages that still reach the inbox.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A 2018 study shows that security indicators can lower the click-through ratio by more than ten points: 48.9% to 37.2% of the users who open spoofed messages.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] SMTP defines message *transport*, not the message *content*.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Thus, it defines the mail *envelope* and its parameters, such as the envelope sender, but not the header (except *trace information*) nor the body of the message itself.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] STD 10 and RFC 5321 define SMTP (the envelope), while STD 11 and RFC 5322 define the message (header and body), formally referred to as the Internet Message Format.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A mail user agent (MUA) knows the *outgoing mail* SMTP server from its configuration.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] An MTA (or a relay server) typically determines which server to connect to by looking up the MX (Mail eXchange) DNS resource record for each recipient's domain name.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The first few lines at the top of the header are usually trusted by the recipient.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Those lines are written by machines in the recipient's Administrative Management Domain (ADMD), which act upon their explicit mandate.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] By contrast, the lines that prove the involvement of **A** and **B**, as well as of the purported author's MUA could be a counterfeit created by **C**.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The `Received:` field shown above is an epoch-making piece of the header.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The `Return-Path:` is written by **E**, the mail delivery agent (MDA), based on the message *envelope*.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Additional trace fields, designed for email authentication, can populate the top of the header.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Normally, messages sent out by an author's ADMD go directly to the destination's MX (that is **B → D** in the figures).
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The sender's ADMD can add authentication tokens only if the message goes through its boxes.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Properly configured proxies appear as part of the author ADMD.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Some ADMDs block outbound connection to port 25 (SMTP) to avoid this.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] This proactive technique is described in RFC 5068.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] In addition, some block inbound SMTP connections from IPs listed as dialup/DSL/cable.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] In this case the author's ADMD is not involved at all.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Some ISPs block port 587, although RFC 5068 clearly says: Access Providers MUST NOT block users from accessing the external Internet using the SUBMISSION port 587.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] SPF allows the receiver to check that an email claimed to have come from a specific domain comes from an IP address authorized by that domain's administrators.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Usually, a domain administrator will authorize the IP addresses used by their own outbound MTAs, including any proxy or smarthost.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The IP address of the sending MTA is guaranteed to be valid by the Transmission Control Protocol, as it establishes the connection by checking that the remote host is reachable.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The receiving mail server receives the `HELO` SMTP command soon after the connection is set up, and a `Mail from:` at the beginning of each message.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The SPF verifier queries the Domain Name System (DNS) for a matching SPF record, which if it exists will specify the IP addresses authorized by that domain's administrator.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The result can be "pass", "fail", or some intermediate result - and systems will generally take this into account in their anti-spam filtering.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] DKIM checks the *message content*, deploying digital signatures.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Rather than using digital certificates, the keys for signature-verification are distributed via the DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] That way, a message gets associated to a domain name.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A DKIM-compliant domain administrator generates one or more pairs of asymmetric keys, then hands private keys to the signing MTA, and publishes public keys on the DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The DNS labels are structured as `*selector*._domainkey.example.com`, where *selector* identifies the key pair, and `_domainkey` is a fixed keyword, followed by the signing domain's name so that publication occurs under the authority of that domain's ADMD.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Just before injecting a message into the SMTP transport system, the signing MTA creates a digital signature that covers selected fields of the header and the body (or just its beginning).
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The signature should cover substantive header fields such as `From:`, `To:`, `Date:`, and `Subject:`, and then is added to the message header itself, as a trace field.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Any number of relays can receive and forward the message and at every hop, the signature can be verified by retrieving the public key from the DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] As long as intermediate relays do not modify signed parts of a message, its DKIM-signatures remain valid.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] DMARC allows the specification of a policy for authenticated messages.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] It is built on top of two existing mechanisms, Sender Policy Framework (SPF) and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A range of other methods have been proposed, but are now either deprecated or have not yet gained widespread support.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] ADSP allowed the specification of a policy for messages signed by the author's domain.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A message had to go through DKIM authentication first, then ADSP could demand a punishing treatment if the message was not signed by the author domain(s) —as per the `From:` header field.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] ADSP was demoted to historic in November 2013.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] VBR adds a vouch to an already authenticated identity.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] This method requires some globally recognized authorities that certify the reputation of domains.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A sender can apply for a reference at a vouching authority.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The reference, if accepted, is published on the DNS branch managed by that authority.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A vouched sender should add a `VBR-Info:` header field to the messages it sends.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] It should also add a DKIM signature, or use some other authentication method, such as SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A receiver, after validating the sender's identity, can verify the vouch claimed in `VBR-Info:` by looking up the reference.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Applications should avoid using this method as a means of authentication.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Nevertheless, it is often carried out and its results, if any, written in the `Received:` header field besides the TCP information required by the SMTP specification.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The IP reverse, confirmed by looking up the IP address of the name just found, is just an indication that the IP was set up properly in the DNS.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The reverse resolution of a range of IP addresses can be delegated to the ADMD that uses them, or can remain managed by the network provider.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] In the latter case, no useful identity related to the message can be obtained.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Looking up a DNSWL (DNS-based whitelist) may provide an assessment of the sender, possibly including its identification.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] RFC 8601 defines a trace header field `Authentication-Results:` where a receiver can record the results of email authentication checks that it carried out.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Multiple results for multiple *methods* can be reported in the same field, separated by semicolons and wrapped as appropriate.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The first token after the field name, `receiver.example.org`, is the ID of the authentication server, a token known as an *authserv-id*.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A receiver supporting RFC 8601 is responsible to remove (or rename) any false header claiming to belong to its domain so that downstream filters cannot get confused.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] However, those filters still need to be configured, as they have to know which identities the domain may use.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] For a Mail User Agent (MUA), it is slightly harder to learn what identities it can trust.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Since users can receive email from multiple domains—e.g., if they have multiple email addresses -— any of those domains could let `Authentication-Results:` fields pass through because they looked neutral.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] That way, a malicious sender can forge an *authserv-id* that the user would trust if the message arrived from a different domain.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] A legitimate `Authentication-Results:` typically appears just above a `Received:` field by the same domain from which the message was relayed.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Additional `Received:` fields may appear between that and the top of the header, as the message got transferred internally between servers belonging to that same, trusted ADMD.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority maintains a registry of Email Authentication Parameters.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] Not all parameters need to be registered, though.
[src:phishing-defense/email-authentication] For example, there can be local "policy" values designed for a site's internal use only, which correspond to local configuration and need no registration.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The term "phishing" was first recorded in 1995 in the cracking toolkit AOHell, but may have been used earlier in the hacker magazine *2600*.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] It is a variation of *fishing* and refers to the use of lures to "fish" for sensitive information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Measures to prevent or reduce the impact of phishing attacks include legislation, user education, public awareness, and technical security measures.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The importance of phishing awareness has increased in both personal and professional settings, with phishing attacks among businesses rising from 72% in 2017 to 86% in 2020, and reaching 94% in 2023.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing techniques and vectors include email spam, vishing (voice phishing), targeted phishing (spear phishing, whaling), smishing (SMS), quishing (QR code), cross-site scripting, and MiTM 2FA attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Research literature identifies phishing as a persistent and evolving cybersecurity threat, with attacks increasingly incorporating advanced techniques such as automation and machine learning.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing attacks, often delivered via email, attempt to trick individuals into giving away sensitive information or login credentials.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Most attacks are "bulk attacks" that are not targeted and are instead sent in bulk to a wide audience.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The goal of the attacker can vary, with common targets including financial institutions, email and cloud productivity providers, and streaming services.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The stolen information or access may be used to steal money, install malware, or spear phish others within the target organization.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Compromised streaming service accounts may also be sold on darknet markets.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] This type of social engineering attack can involve sending fraudulent emails or messages that appear to be from a trusted source, such as a bank or government agency.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These messages typically redirect to a fake login page where users are prompted to enter their credentials.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In many cases, these messages are designed to create urgency or trust by imitating legitimate communications, encouraging victims to disclose sensitive information such as login credentials or financial details.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Spear phishing attacks are often more effective than general phishing attempts because they are tailored to specific individuals and leverage personal or organizational information to increase credibility and success rates.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These attacks often target executives or those in financial departments with access to sensitive financial data and services.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Spear phishing often employs multiple communication methods at the same time including email, SMS, and calls to create a false sense of urgency.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Accountancy and audit firms are particularly vulnerable to spear phishing due to the value of the information their employees have access to.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The Russian government-run Threat Group-4127 (Fancy Bear; GRU Unit 26165) targeted Hillary Clinton's 2016 presidential campaign with spear phishing attacks on over 1,800 Google accounts, using the accounts-google.com domain to threaten targeted users.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A study on spear phishing susceptibility among different age groups found that 43% of youth aged 18–25 years and 58% of older users clicked on simulated phishing links in daily e‑mails over 21 days.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Older women had the highest susceptibility, which declined among young users during the study but remained stable among older individuals.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Voice over IP (VoIP) is used in vishing or voice phishing attacks, where attackers make automated phone calls to large numbers of people, often using text-to-speech synthesizers, claiming fraudulent activity on their accounts.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The attackers spoof the calling phone number to appear as if it is coming from a legitimate bank or institution.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The victim is then prompted to enter sensitive information or connected to a live person who uses social engineering tactics to obtain information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Vishing takes advantage of the public's lower awareness and trust in voice telephony compared to email phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] SMS phishing or smishing is a phishing attack using mobile text messages to deliver bait messages.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The victim is usually asked to click a link, call a phone number, or contact an email address provided by the attacker.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] They may be asked to provide private information, such as login credentials.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Attackers may pretend to be government officers, customer support, shippers, colleague, boss, or a wrong number.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The range of possibilities requires permanent vigilance and critical thinking to detect attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Smishing messages may be identified when they come from unusual phone numbers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The difficulty in identifying illegitimate links can be compounded on mobile devices due to the limited display of URLs in mobile browsers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These kinds of scams apply various forms of social engineering including scammers that pretend to be financial institutions or customer service.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Page hijacking involves redirecting users to malicious websites or exploit kits by compromising legitimate web pages, often using cross site scripting.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Hackers may insert exploit kits such as MPack into compromised websites to exploit legitimate users visiting the server.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Page hijacking can also involve insertion of malicious inline frames, allowing exploit kits to load.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] This tactic is often used together with watering hole attacks on corporate targets.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In "quishing" (QR code phishing), scammers exploit the convenience of QR codes to trick users into giving up sensitive data, by scanning a code containing an embedded malicious web site link.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Unlike traditional phishing, which relies on deceptive links in emails or websites, quishing uses QR codes to bypass email filters and appear less suspicious, as victims may not scrutinize them as carefully as URLs.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The bogus codes may be sent by email, social media, or hard copy stickers placed over legitimate QR codes on such as on advertisements or car park notices.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] When victims scan a code, they may be redirected to a fake website designed to steal personal information, login credentials, or financial details.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] As QR codes become more widely used for things like payments, event check-ins, and product information, quishing is emerging as a significant concern for digital security.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Cybercriminals can also merge QR Code phishing with Browser-in-The-Browser (BiTB) to trick users into approving the attacker's two-factor access.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These trends indicate the growing sophistication of quishing tactics .
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Users are advised to exercise caution when scanning unfamiliar QR codes and ensure they are from trusted sources, although the UK's National Cyber Security Centre rates the risk as lower than other types of lure.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Traditional phishing attacks are typically limited to capturing user credentials directly inputted into fraudulent websites.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] However, the advent of Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) phishing techniques has significantly advanced the sophistication of these attacks, enabling cybercriminals to bypass two-factor authentication (2FA) mechanisms during a user's active session on a web service.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] MitM phishing attacks employ intermediary tools that intercept communication between the user and the legitimate service.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Evilginx, originally created as an open-source tool for penetration testing and ethical hacking, has been repurposed by cybercriminals for MitM attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Evilginx works like a middleman, passing information between the victim and the real website without saving passwords or login codes.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] This makes it harder for security systems to detect, since they usually look for phishing sites that store stolen data.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] By grabbing login tokens and session cookies instantly, attackers can break into accounts and use them just like the real user, for as long as the session stays active.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Attackers employ various methods, including phishing emails, social engineering tactics, or distributing malicious links via social media platforms.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Once the victim interacts with the counterfeit site, the MitM tool intercepts the authentication process, effectively bypassing 2FA protections.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing attacks often involve creating fake links that appear to be from a legitimate organization.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These links may use misspelled URLs or subdomains to deceive the user.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Another tactic is to make the link's displayed text appear trustworthy, while actually linking to the phisher's site.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] To check the destination of a link, many email clients and web browsers show the URL in the status bar when the mouse is hovering over it.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] However, some phishers may be able to bypass this security measure.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Internationalized domain names (IDNs) can be exploited via IDN spoofing or homograph attacks to allow attackers to create fake websites with visually identical addresses to legitimate ones.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These attacks have been used by phishers to disguise malicious URLs using open URL redirectors on trusted websites.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] An example of this is in `http://www.exаmple.com/`, where the third character is not the Latin letter 'a', but instead the Cyrillic character 'а'.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] When the victim uses the link, unaware of the replaced letter, they get redirected to the malicious site `http://www.xn--exmple-4nf.com/`.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing often uses social engineering techniques to trick users into performing actions such as clicking a link or opening an attachment, or revealing sensitive information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] It often involves pretending to be a trusted entity and creating a sense of urgency, like threatening to close or seize a victim's bank or insurance account.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] An alternative technique to impersonation-based phishing is the use of fake news articles to trick victims into clicking on a malicious link.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These links often lead to fake websites that appear legitimate, but are actually run by attackers who may try to install malware or present fake "virus" notifications to the victim.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A major concern in contemporary contexts is the potential for Generative AI to exacerbate phishing and social engineering.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] AI generation for both texts and images improves the realism in visual content, leading to more connective forms of manipulating.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] They also strengthen the attackers ability to target their victims and ease automation processes that enhance the attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Early phishing techniques can be traced back to the 1990s, when black hat hackers and the warez community used AOL to steal credit card information and commit other online crimes.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The term "phishing" is said to have been coined by Khan C.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Smith, a well-known spammer and hacker, and its first recorded mention was found in the hacking tool AOHell, which was released in 1994.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] AOHell allowed hackers to impersonate AOL staff and send instant messages to victims asking them to reveal their passwords.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In response, AOL implemented measures to prevent phishing and eventually shut down the warez scene on their platform.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In the 2000s, phishing attacks became more organized and targeted.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The first known direct attempt against a payment system, E-gold, occurred in June 2001, and shortly after the September 11 attacks, a "post-9/11 id check" phishing attack followed.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The first known phishing attack against a retail bank was reported in September 2003.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Between May 2004 and May 2005, approximately 1.2 million computer users in the United States suffered losses caused by phishing, totaling approximately US$929 million.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing was recognized as a fully organized part of the black market, and specializations emerged on a global scale that provided phishing software for payment, which were assembled and implemented into phishing campaigns by organized gangs.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The United Kingdom banking sector suffered from phishing attacks, with losses from web banking fraud almost doubling in 2005 compared to 2004.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In 2006, almost half of phishing thefts were committed by groups operating through the Russian Business Network based in St.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Email scams posing as the Internal Revenue Service were also used to steal sensitive data from U.S. taxpayers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Social networking sites are a prime target of phishing, since the personal details in such sites can be used in identity theft; In 2007, 3.6 million adults lost US$3.2 billion due to phishing attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The Anti-Phishing Working Group reported receiving 115,370 phishing email reports from consumers with US and China hosting more than 25% of the phishing pages each in the third quarter of 2009.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing in the 2010s saw a significant increase in the number of attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In 2011, the master keys for RSA SecurID security tokens were stolen through a phishing attack.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Chinese phishing campaigns also targeted high-ranking officials in the US and South Korean governments and military, as well as Chinese political activists.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] According to Ghosh, phishing attacks increased from 187,203 in 2010 to 445,004 in 2012.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In August 2013, Outbrain suffered a spear-phishing attack, and in November 2013, 110 million customer and credit card records were stolen from Target customers through a phished subcontractor account. subsequently, CEO and IT security staff were dismissed.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In August 2014, iCloud leaks of celebrity photos were based on phishing e-mails sent to victims that looked like they came from Apple or Google.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In November 2014, phishing attacks on ICANN gained administrative access to the Centralized Zone Data System; also gained was data about users in the system - and access to ICANN's public Governmental Advisory Committee wiki, blog, and whois information portal.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Fancy Bear was linked to spear-phishing attacks against the Pentagon email system in August 2015, and the group used a zero-day exploit of Java in a spear-phishing attack on the White House and NATO.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Fancy Bear carried out spear phishing attacks on email addresses associated with the Democratic National Committee in the first quarter of 2016.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In August 2016, members of the Bundestag and political parties such as Linken-faction leader Sahra Wagenknecht, Junge Union, and the CDU of Saarland were targeted by spear-phishing attacks suspected to be carried out by Fancy Bear.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In August 2016, the World Anti-Doping Agency reported the receipt of phishing emails sent to users of its database claiming to be official WADA, but consistent with the Russian hacking group Fancy Bear.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In 2017, 76% of organizations experienced phishing attacks, with nearly half of the information security professionals surveyed reporting an increase from 2016.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In the first half of 2017, businesses and residents of Qatar were hit with over 93,570 phishing events in a three-month span.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In August 2017, customers of Amazon faced the Amazon Prime Day phishing attack, when hackers sent out seemingly legitimate deals to customers of Amazon.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] When Amazon's customers attempted to make purchases using the "deals", the transaction would not be completed, prompting the retailer's customers to input data that could be compromised and stolen.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In 2018, the company block.one, which developed the EOS.IO blockchain, was attacked by a phishing group who sent phishing emails to all customers aimed at intercepting the user's cryptocurrency wallet key, and a later attack targeted airdrop tokens.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing attacks have evolved in the 2020s to include elements of social engineering, as demonstrated by the July 15, 2020, Twitter breach.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In this case, a 17-year-old hacker and accomplices set up a fake website resembling Twitter's internal VPN provider used by remote working employees.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Posing as helpdesk staff, they called multiple Twitter employees, directing them to submit their credentials to the fake VPN website.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Using the details supplied by the unsuspecting employees, they were able to seize control of several high-profile user accounts, including those of Barack Obama, Elon Musk, Joe Biden, and Apple Inc.'s company account.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The hackers then sent messages to Twitter followers soliciting Bitcoin, promising to double the transaction value in return.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The hackers collected 12.86 BTC (about $117,000 at the time).
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In the 2020s, phishing as a service (PhaaS) platforms like Darcula allow attackers to easily fake trusted websites.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] There are anti-phishing websites which publish exact messages that have been recently circulating the internet, such as FraudWatch International and Millersmiles.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Such sites often provide specific details about the particular messages.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] As recently as 2007, the adoption of anti-phishing strategies by businesses needing to protect personal and financial information was low.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] There are several different techniques to combat phishing, including legislation and technology created specifically to protect against phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These techniques include steps that can be taken by individuals, as well as by organizations.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phone, web site, and email phishing can now be reported to authorities, as described below.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Effective phishing education, including conceptual knowledge and feedback, is an important part of any organization's anti-phishing strategy.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] While there is limited data on the effectiveness of education in reducing susceptibility to phishing, much information on the threat is available online.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Simulated phishing campaigns, in which organizations test their employees' training by sending fake phishing emails, are commonly used to assess their effectiveness.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] One example is a study by the National Library of Medicine, in which an organization received 858,200 emails during a 1-month testing period, with 139,400 (16%) being marketing and 18,871 (2%) being identified as potential threats.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These campaigns are often used in the healthcare industry, as healthcare data is a valuable target for hackers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These campaigns are just one of the ways that organizations are working to combat phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Nearly all legitimate e-mail messages from companies to their customers contain an item of information that is not readily available to phishers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Some companies, for example PayPal, always address their customers by their username in emails, so if an email addresses the recipient in a generic fashion ("Dear PayPal customer") it is likely to be an attempt at phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Furthermore, PayPal offers various methods to determine spoof emails and advises users to forward suspicious emails to their spoof@PayPal.com domain to investigate and warn other customers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Emails from banks and credit card companies often include partial account numbers, but research has shown that people tend to not differentiate between the first and last digits.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A study on phishing attacks in game environments found that educational games can effectively educate players against information disclosures and can increase awareness on phishing risk thus mitigating risks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The Anti-Phishing Working Group, one of the largest anti-phishing organizations in the world, produces regular report on trends in phishing attacks.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A wide range of technical approaches are available to prevent phishing attacks reaching users or to prevent them from successfully capturing sensitive information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Specialized spam filters can reduce the number of phishing emails that reach their addressees' inboxes.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These filters use a number of techniques including machine learning and natural language processing approaches to classify phishing emails, and reject email with forged addresses.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Another popular approach to fighting phishing is to maintain a list of known malicious sites and verify URLs against that list in real time.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These browsers often source their intelligence through trusted security partners or specialized browser extensions, such as Google Safe Browsing, Microsoft Defender Smartscreen, Bitdefender TrafficLight, uBlock Origin Lite, Netcraft Extension and Blue Arca PhishGuard.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Web browsers such as Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Mozilla Firefox, Safari, and Opera all contain this type of anti-phishing measure.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Firefox 2 used Google anti-phishing software.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Opera 9.1 uses live blacklists from Phishtank, cyscon and GeoTrust, as well as live whitelists from GeoTrust.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Some implementations of this approach send the visited URLs to a central service to be checked, which has raised concerns about privacy.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] According to a 2026 study by AV-Comparatives, Avast Secure Browser and Norton Security Browser were found to be most effective at detecting fraudulent sites, blocking 94% of phishing URLs, while Google Chrome blocked 72%.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] An approach introduced in mid-2006 involves switching to a special DNS service that filters out known phishing domains.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] To mitigate the problem of phishing sites impersonating a victim site by embedding its images (such as logos), several site owners have altered the images to send a message to the visitor that a site may be fraudulent.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The image may be moved to a new filename and the original permanently replaced, or a server can detect that the image was not requested as part of normal browsing, and instead send a warning image.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The Bank of America website was one of several that asked users to select a personal image (marketed as SiteKey) and displayed this user-selected image with any forms that request a password.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Users of the bank's online services were instructed to enter a password only when they saw the image they selected.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The bank has since discontinued the use of SiteKey.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Several studies suggest that few users refrain from entering their passwords when images are absent.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In addition, this feature (like other forms of two-factor authentication) is susceptible to other attacks, such as those suffered by Scandinavian bank Nordea in late 2005, and Citibank in 2006.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A similar system, in which an automatically generated "Identity Cue" consisting of a colored word within a colored box is displayed to each website user, is in use at other financial institutions.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Security skins are a related technique that involves overlaying a user-selected image onto the login form as a visual cue that the form is legitimate.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Unlike the website-based image schemes, however, the image itself is shared only between the user and the browser, and not between the user and the website.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The scheme also relies on a mutual authentication protocol, which makes it less vulnerable to attacks that affect user-only authentication schemes.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Still another technique relies on a dynamic grid of images that is different for each login attempt.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The user must identify the pictures that fit their pre-chosen categories (such as dogs, cars and flowers).
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Only after they have correctly identified the pictures that fit their categories are they allowed to enter their alphanumeric password to complete the login.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Several companies offer digital risk protection (DRP) services to detect, block, and take down malicious websites, social accounts, applications, and digital infrastructure impersonating legitimate organizations.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] While early tools required extensive manual oversight, modern vendors like Netcraft, ZeroFox and Recorded Future have moved toward higher levels of automation to combat the speed of AI-driven phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Individuals can contribute by reporting phishing to both volunteer and industry groups, such as cyscon or PhishTank.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing web pages and emails can be reported to Google.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Organizations can implement two factor or multi-factor authentication (MFA), which requires a user to use at least 2 factors when logging in.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] (For example, a user must both present a smart card and a password).
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] This mitigates some risk, in the event of a successful phishing attack, the stolen password on its own cannot be reused to further breach the protected system.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] However, there are several attack methods which can defeat many of the typical systems.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] MFA schemes such as WebAuthn address this issue by design.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Federal Trade Commission filed the first phishing lawsuit, against a Californian teenager suspected of creating a webpage mimicking America Online and stealing credit card information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Other countries have followed this lead by tracing and arresting phishers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] A phishing kingpin, Valdir Paulo de Almeida, was arrested in Brazil for leading one of the largest phishing crime rings, which in two years stole between US$18 million and US$37 million.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] UK authorities jailed two men in June 2005 for their role in a phishing scam, in a case connected to the U.S.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Secret Service Operation Firewall, which targeted notorious "carder" websites.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In 2006, Japanese police arrested eight people for creating fake Yahoo Japan websites, netting themselves ¥100 million (US$870,000) and the FBI detained a gang of sixteen in the U.S. and Europe in Operation Cardkeeper.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Senator Patrick Leahy introduced the Anti-Phishing Act of 2005 to Congress in the United States on March 1, 2005.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] This bill aimed to impose fines of up to $250,000 and prison sentences of up to five years on criminals who used fake websites and emails to defraud consumers.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In the UK, the Fraud Act 2006 introduced a general offense of fraud punishable by up to ten years in prison and prohibited the development or possession of phishing kits with the intention of committing fraud.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Companies have also joined the effort to crack down on phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] On March 31, 2005, Microsoft filed 117 federal lawsuits in the U.S.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] District Court for the Western District of Washington.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The lawsuits accuse "John Doe" defendants of obtaining passwords and confidential information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] March 2005 also saw a partnership between Microsoft and the Australian government teaching law enforcement officials how to combat various cyber crimes, including phishing.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Microsoft announced a planned further 100 lawsuits outside the U.S. in March 2006, followed by the commencement, as of November 2006, of 129 lawsuits mixing criminal and civil actions.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] AOL reinforced its efforts against phishing in early 2006 with three lawsuits seeking a total of US$18 million under the 2005 amendments to the Virginia Computer Crimes Act, and Earthlink has joined in by helping to identify six men subsequently charged with phishing fraud in Connecticut.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] In January 2007, Jeffrey Brett Goodin of California became the first defendant convicted by a jury under the provisions of the CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] He was found guilty of sending thousands of emails to AOL users, while posing as the company's billing department, which prompted customers to submit personal and credit card information.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Facing a possible 101 years in prison for the CAN-SPAM violation and ten other counts including wire fraud, the unauthorized use of credit cards, and the misuse of AOL's trademark, he was sentenced to serve 70 months.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Goodin had been in custody since failing to appear for an earlier court hearing and began serving his prison term immediately.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Phishing is the leading cause of healthcare data breaches in the United States, with the U.S.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] Department of Health and Human Services Office for Civil Rights consistently identifying email-based attacks as the most common initial attack vector in breaches reported under the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Breach Notification Rule.
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities to implement security awareness and training programs for their workforce, including training on procedures for guarding against and detecting malicious software and monitoring log-in attempts (45 CFR 164.308(a)(5)).
[src:phishing-defense/phishing] These proposals were prompted in part by large-scale healthcare breaches initiated through phishing, including the 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack that compromised the records of approximately 100 million individuals.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The list of authorized sending hosts and IP addresses for a domain is published in the DNS records for that domain.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Sender Policy Framework is defined in RFC 7208 dated April 2014 as a "proposed standard".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The first public mention of the concept was in 2000 but went mostly unnoticed.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] No mention was made of the concept again until a first attempt at an SPF-like specification was published in 2002 on the IETF "namedroppers" mailing list by Dana Valerie Reese, who was unaware of the 2000 mention of the idea.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The very next day, Paul Vixie posted his own SPF-like specification on the same list.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] These posts ignited a lot of interest, led to the forming of the IETF Anti-Spam Research Group (ASRG) and their mailing list, where the SPF idea was further developed.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Among the proposals submitted to the ASRG were "Reverse MX" (RMX) by Hadmut Danisch, and "Designated Mailer Protocol" (DMP) by Gordon Fecyk.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In June 2003, Meng Weng Wong merged the RMX and DMP specifications and solicited suggestions from others.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Over the next six months, a large number of changes were made and a large community had started working on SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Originally SPF stood for *Sender Permitted From* and was sometimes also called *SMTP+SPF*; but its name was changed to *Sender Policy Framework* in February 2004.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In early 2004, the IETF created the MARID working group and tried to use SPF and Microsoft's CallerID proposal as the basis for what is now known as Sender ID; but this collapsed due to technical and licensing conflicts.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The SPF community returned to the original "classic" version of SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In July 2005, this version of the specification was approved by the IESG as an IETF *experiment*, inviting the community to observe SPF during the two years following publication.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] On April 28, 2006, the SPF RFC was published as experimental RFC 4408.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] On April 25, 2014 IETF published SPF in RFC 7208 as a "proposed standard" which "obsoleted" RFC 4408 and, as of May 2026, RFC 7208 had not been obsoleted.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol permits any computer to send email claiming to be from any source address.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] This is exploited by spammers and scammers who often use forged email addresses, making it more difficult to trace a message back to its source, and easy for spammers to hide their identity in order to avoid responsibility.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] It is also used in phishing techniques, where users can be duped into disclosing private information in response to an email purportedly sent by an organization such as a bank.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] SPF allows the owner of an Internet domain to specify which computers are authorized to send mail with envelope-from addresses in that domain, using Domain Name System (DNS) records.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Receivers verifying the SPF information in TXT records may reject messages from unauthorized sources before receiving the body of the message.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Thus, the principles of operation are similar to those of DNS-based blackhole lists (DNSBL), except that SPF uses the authority delegation scheme of the Domain Name System.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Current practice requires the use of TXT records, just as early implementations did.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] For a while a new record type (SPF, type 99) was registered and made available in common DNS software.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Use of TXT records for SPF was intended as a transitional mechanism at the time.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The experimental RFC, RFC 4408, section 3.1.1, suggested "an SPF-compliant domain name SHOULD have SPF records of both RR types".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The proposed standard, RFC 7208, says "use of alternative DNS RR types was supported in SPF's experimental phase but has been discontinued".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The envelope-from address is transmitted at the beginning of the SMTP dialog.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] If the server rejects the domain, the unauthorized client should receive a rejection message, and if that client was a relaying message transfer agent (MTA), a bounce message to the original envelope-from address may be generated.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] If the server accepts the domain, and subsequently also accepts the recipients and the body of the message, it should insert a Return-Path field in the message header in order to save the envelope-from address.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] While the address in the Return-Path often matches other originator addresses in the mail header such as the *header-from*, this is not necessarily the case, and SPF does not prevent forgery of these other addresses such as *sender* header.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Spammers can send email with an SPF PASS result if they have an account in a domain with a sender policy, or abuse a compromised system in this domain.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] However, doing so makes the spammer easier to trace.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] SPF benefits owners of email addresses that are forged in the Return-Path.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] They receive large numbers of unsolicited error messages and other auto-replies.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] If such receivers use SPF to specify their legitimate source IP addresses and indicate FAIL result for all other addresses, receivers checking SPF can reject forgeries, thus reducing or eliminating the amount of backscatter.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] SPF has potential advantages beyond helping identify unwanted mail.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In particular, if a sender provides SPF information, then receivers can use SPF PASS results in combination with an allow list to identify known reliable senders.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Scenarios like compromised systems and shared sending mailers limit this use.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] If a domain publishes an SPF record, spammers and phishers are less likely to forge emails pretending to be from that domain, because the forged emails are more likely to be caught in spam filters which check the SPF record.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Therefore, an SPF-protected domain is less attractive to spammers and phishers.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Because an SPF-protected domain is less attractive as a spoofed address, it is less likely to be denylisted by spam filters and so ultimately the legitimate email from the domain is more likely to get through.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The next hop does not allowlist the forwarder.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] This is a necessary and obvious feature of SPF – checks *behind* the "border" MTA (MX) of the receiver cannot work directly.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Publishers of SPF FAIL policies must accept the risk of their legitimate emails being rejected or bounced.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] They should test (e.g., with a SOFTFAIL policy) until they are satisfied with the results.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] See below for a list of alternatives to plain message forwarding.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] For an empty Return-Path as used in error messages and other auto-replies, an SPF check of the HELO identity is mandatory.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] With a bogus HELO identity the result NONE would not help, but for valid host names SPF also protects the HELO identity.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] This SPF feature was always supported as an option for receivers, and later SPF drafts including the final specification recommend to check the HELO always.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] This allows receivers to allowlist sending mailers based on a HELO PASS, or to reject all mails after a HELO FAIL.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] It can also be used in reputation systems (any allow or deny list is a simple case of a reputation system).
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Thus, the key issue in SPF is the specification for the new DNS information that domains set and receivers use.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The following words provide *mechanisms* to use to determine if a domain is eligible to send mail.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The "ip4" and "a" specify the systems permitted to send messages for the given domain.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The "-all" at the end specifies that, if the previous *mechanisms* did not match, the message should be rejected.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] The *modifiers* allow for future extensions to the framework.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] As soon as SPF implementations detect syntax errors in a sender policy they **must** abort the evaluation with result PERMERROR.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Skipping erroneous *mechanisms* cannot work as expected, therefore `include:bad.example` and `redirect=bad.example` also cause a PERMERROR.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Another safeguard is the maximum of ten mechanisms querying DNS, i.e. any mechanism except from IP4, IP6, and ALL.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Implementations can abort the evaluation with result TEMPERROR when it takes too long or a DNS query times out or they can continue pretending that the query returned no data —which is called a "void lookup".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] However, they **must** return PERMERROR if the policy directly or indirectly needs more than ten queries for *mechanisms*.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In addition, they **should** return PERMERROR as soon as more than two "void lookups" have been encountered.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Any `redirect=` also counts towards this *processing limits*.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] A typical SPF HELO policy `v=spf1 a mx ip4:192.0.2.0 -all` may execute four or more DNS queries: (1) TXT record (SPF type was obsoleted by RFC 7208), (2) A or AAAA for mechanism `a`, (3) MX record and (4+) A or AAAA for each MX name, for mechanism `mx`.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Except the first one, all those queries count towards the limit of 10.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In addition if, for example, the sender has an IPv6 address, while its name and its two MX names have only IPv4 addresses, then the evaluation of the first two mechanisms already results in more than two void lookups and hence PERMERROR.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Mechanisms `ip4`, `ip6` and `all` need no DNS lookup.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] To enable rapid testing and deployment, initial versions of SPF checked for its setting in the DNS TXT record of the sending domain - even though this record was traditionally supposed to be free-form text with no semantics attached.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Although in July 2005, IANA assigned a specific Resource Record type 99 to SPF the uptake of was never high, and having two mechanisms was confusing for users.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] As SPF increasingly prevents spammers from spoofing the envelope-from address, many have moved to only spoof the address in the From field of the mail header, which is actually displayed to the recipient rather than only processed by the recipient's message transfer agent (MTA).
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] SPF (or DKIM) can be used together with DMARC though, to also check the From field of the mail header.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Custom proprietary implementations are required to protect against such display name spoofing and cannot utilize SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Anti-spam software such as SpamAssassin version 3.0.0 and ASSP implement SPF.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Many mail transfer agents (MTAs) support SPF directly such as Courier, CommuniGate Pro, Wildcat, MDaemon, and Microsoft Exchange, or have patches or plug-ins available that support SPF, including Postfix, Sendmail, Exim, qmail, and Qpsmtpd.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] As of 2017, more than eight million domains publish SPF FAIL `-all` policies.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In a survey published in 2007, 5% of the `.com` and `.net` domains had some kind of SPF policy.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In 2009, a continuous survey run at Nokia Research reports that 51% of the tested domains specify an SPF policy.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] These results can include trivial policies like `v=spf1 ?all`.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In April 2007, BITS, a division of the Financial Services Roundtable, published email security recommendations for its members including SPF deployment.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In 2008, the Messaging Anti-Abuse Working Group (MAAWG) published a paper about email authentication covering SPF, Sender ID, and DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM).
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In their "Sender Best Communication Practices" the MAAWG stated: "At the very least, senders should incorporate SPF records for their mailing domains".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In 2015, the Messaging Anti-Abuse Working Group (MAAWG) revised a paper about email authentication covering SPF, DomainKeys Identified Mail (DKIM), and DMARC (DMARC).
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] In their revised "Sender Best Communication Practices" the MAAWG stated: "Authentication supports transparency by further identifying the sender(s) of a message, while also contributing to the reduction or elimination of spoofed and forged addresses".
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] From February 1, 2024, Google requires SPF or DKIM for all domains sending emails to Gmail accounts.
[src:phishing-defense/sender-policy-framework] Bulk senders (5000+ emails per day) are required to have SPF, DKIM, and DMARC setup for their domains.
